FLIGHT CRITICAL SYSTEMS RESEARCH (FCSR) TASK ORDER STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW) 1.0 TASK ORDER TITLE: SOFTWARE ANOMALY TAXONOMY VALIDATION 2.0 BACKGROUND: NASA S AVIATION SAFETY (AVSAFE) PROGRAM S INTEGRATED VEHICLE HEALTH MANAGEMENT (IVHM) PROJECT IS PURSUING FOUNDATIONAL RESEARCH IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF TECHNOLOGIES FOR AUTOMATED DETECTION, DIAGNOSIS, PROGNOSTICS, AND MITIGATION OF ADVERSE EVENTS DUE TO AIRCRAFT SOFTWARE. THIS EFFORT IS BEING CONDUCTED UNDER THE SUB-ELEMENT ENTITLED SOFTWARE HEALTH MANAGEMENT IN VERSION 2.0 OF THE IVHM TECHNICAL PLAN ( HTTP://WWW.AERONAUTICS.NASA.GOV/NRA_PDF/IVHM_TECH_PLAN_C1.PDF ), WHICH SEEKS TO EXPLORE SOFTWARE HEALTH MANAGEMENT IN THE CONTEXT OF SYSTEM LEVEL DEPENDABILITY CASES -- A CENTRAL RECOMMENDATION OF A RECENT NATIONAL ACADEMIES REPORT (JACKSON, D.; ET AL. SOFTWARE FOR DEPENDABLE SYSTEMS: SUFFICIENT EVIDENCE? NATIONAL ACADEMIES PRESS, 2007, HTTP://WWW7.NATIONALACADEMIES.ORG/CSTB/PUB_DEPENDABLE.HTML ). UNDER PREVIOUS FLIGHT CRITICAL SYSTEMS RESEARCH (FCSR) TASKING (NNL07AB06T CONCEPT DEVELOPMENT FOR SOFTWARE HEALTH MANAGEMENT ) A CATALOG OF HISTORICAL AIRCRAFT SOFTWARE ANOMALIES, UNCOVERED DURING VERIFICATION AND VALIDATION ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED THROUGHOUT THE SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT LIFECYCLE, WAS COMPILED, AND A COMPREHENSIVE FAILURE TAXONOMY FOR SOFTWARE FAILURES IN AIRCRAFT SYSTEMS WAS DEVELOPED. THE COMPILATION OF THE CATALOG AND TAXONOMY WAS DERIVED THROUGH INSPECTION, BY SUBJECT MATTER EXPERTS, OF TEXT-BASED REPORT ARCHIVES OF SELECTED ADVANCED FLIGHT-CRITICAL SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS. 3.0 OBJECTIVE: THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS TASK IS TO INVESTIGATE THE USE OF AUTO-CLASSIFICATION ALGORITHMS FOR PURPOSES OF REPLICATING AND VALIDATING THE SOFTWARE FAILURE TAXONOMY DEVELOPED UNDER TASK NNL07AB06T. THE INVESTIGATION WILL INCLUDE THE APPLICATION OF THE CLASSIFICATION PARAMETERS AND TOOLSET TO LARGE DATASETS THAT WOULD OTHERWISE BE UNSUITABLE FOR INSPECTION BY SUBJECT MATTER EXPERTS. THE RESULTING TAXONOMY OF ANOMALIES WILL SERVE AS A CANDIDATE FOR SOFTWARE HEALTH MANAGEMENT FRAMEWORKS. 4.0 DESCRIPTION OF TASK REQUIREMENTS: THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PERFORM THE FOLLOWING TASKS: TASK 1: CLASSIFICATION TOOL A) CONFIGURE, ASSESS AND SELECT AN AUTO-CLASSIFICATION ALGORITHM, SUCH AS THE MARIANA AUTO-CLASSIFIER ALGORITHM (HTTPS://DASHLINK.ARC.NASA.GOV/ALGORITHM/MARIANA/), FOR APPLICATION TO SOFTWARE ANOMALY DETECTION. TASK 2: TAXONOMY VALIDATION A) APPLY CLASSIFICATION TOOL SELECTED IN TASK 1 TO DATASETS USED FOR DERIVING THE TAXONOMY GENERATED UNDER TASK NNL07AB06T. B) APPLY THE CLASSIFICATION TOOL SELECTED IN TASK 1 TO REPRESENTATIVE DATASETS COMPRISED OF A MINIMUM OF 1,000 ANOMALY RECORDS. 5.0 PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE: 11 MONTHS FROM TASK ORDER AWARD DATE. 6.0 TRAVEL: IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT THE FOLLOWING TRIPS WILL BE REQUIRED: DESCRIPTION WHERE PERSONS NO. FOLLOWING THE CREW EXPLORATION VEHICLE (CEV) SMART BUYER DESIGN EFFORT, THE NASA ENGINEERING AND SAFETY CENTER HAS BEEN PERFORMING FOLLOW-ON WORK TO DETERMINE IF THERE ARE SIGNIFICANT IMPROVEMENTS OR EFFICIENCIES THAT CAN BE GAINED FROM A COMPOSITE PRESSURIZED VESSEL DESIGN.  THE TEAM DEVELOPED THREE DIFFERENT COMPOSITE CONCEPTS THAT PROVIDED THE NECESSARY DATA TO SHOW THAT A COMPOSITE PRESSURIZED VESSEL IS ACHIEVABLE AND COMPARABLE TO THE METALLIC DESIGNS.  BASED ON THE RESULTS OF THIS PRELIMINARY DESIGN WORK, THE ASSOCIATE ADMINISTRATOR FOR EXPLORATION SYSTEMS MISSION DIRECTORATE HAS REQUESTED THAT THE NESC FORM AN NASA/DOD/INDUSTRY PARTNERSHIP FOR COMPOSITE SPACECRAFT STRUCTURAL DESIGN TO FURTHER EXPLORE AND QUANTIFY THESE POTENTIAL IMPROVEMENTS.  THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS EFFORT IS TO EXAMINE THE EFFICACY OF BUILDING COMPOSITE CREW MODULES FOR FUTURE HUMAN SPACE SYSTEMS. OBJECTIVES:   IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT FUTURE SPACECRAFT WILL REQUIRE INEXPENSIVE AND LIGHTWEIGHT STRUCTURES TO ACHIEVE MASS REQUIREMENTS FOR MISSIONS TO LOW EARTH ORBIT, THE LUNAR SURFACE, AND BEYOND.  POLYMERIC COMPOSITE MATERIALS MAY PROVIDE REQUIRED COST AND MASS SAVINGS DUE TO THEIR HIGHER SPECIFIC STRENGTH, REDUCED MANUFACTURING COSTS AND PART COUNT, IMPROVED DURABILITY, ETC.    IN ORDER TO ACCELERATE SCHEDULE AND MINIMIZE RISK FOR A NEW NASA LED COMPOSITE PRESSURE SHELL APPLICATION, NASA WILL LEVERAGE EXISTING DESIGN AND MANUFACTURING METHODOLOGIES PERTAINING TO 3D WOVEN PI PREFORMS.  THE RELEVANT EXPERIENCE WAS DEVELOPED ON PROGRAMS SUCH AS THE JOINT STRIKE FIGHTER (JSF) AND COMPOSITE AFFORDABILITY INITIATIVE (CAI).   DESCRIPTION OF TASKS TO BE PERFORMED:  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE DETAILED INFORMATION IN DESIGN AREAS SUCH AS PI PREFORM TERMINATIONS, PI PREFORM INTERSECTIONS, PI PREFORM ALLOWABLE CAPABILITY, PI PREFORM CAPABILITY WITH OVERWRAPS.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL ALSO PROVIDE DETAILED SUPPORT FOR MANUFACTURING SUCH AS SURFACE PREPARATION METHODS, BAGGING SCHEMES, OVERPRESS PARTS, GAP ALLOWANCES, AND QUALITY CONTROL INDICATORS.  FINALLY, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE TESTING SUPPORT, WHICH SHALL INCLUDE FIXTURES, TEST METHODS, AND ANALYSIS CORRELATION METHODS.   SUBTASK 1 - PARTICIPATION ON THE ON-SITE COMPOSITE CREW MODULE TEAM THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PARTICIPATE WITH THE NASA LED TEAM IN DEVELOPING RECOMMENDATION FOR TECHNICAL AREAS SPECIFIED BELOW.  THE PARTICIPATION INCLUDES ON-SITE INTERACTION WITH THE COMPOSITE CREW MODULE TEAM (NASA + CONTRACTORS).  CO-LOCATION EVENTS WILL BE AS NECESSARY.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PLAN ON A 1-WEEK TRIP EVERY 3 MONTHS TO EITHER NASA/GSFC (GREENBELT, MD), NASA/MSFC (HUNTSVILLE, AL) OR MANUFACTURE FACILITY (TBD LOCATION) FOR THE PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE.  AS A MEMBER OF THE COMPOSITE CREW MODULE TEAM, THE VENDOR SHALL WORK WITH OTHER INDUSTRIAL PARTNERS WHO ARE ALREADY A PART OF THE TEAM.   INDUSTRIAL PARTNERS NOW INCLUDE ATK, NORTHROP GRUMMAN, SWALES, COLLIER INDUSTRIES, AND SDA, INC.   SUBTASK 2  PI PERFORM COUPON TESTING   THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE THE NECESSARY MANPOWER AND EXPERTISE TO SUPPORT THE INITIAL PI PREFORM COUPON TESTING, BASED ON THEIR EXTENSIVE WORK DEVELOPING DESIGN ALLOWABLES FOR THE JSF PROGRAM AND SIMILAR COUPON TESTING FOR THE CAI PROGRAM.  AS PART OF THIS SUPPORT, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL DESIGN AND DELIVER FIXTURES FOR COUPON BONDING, SILICONE OVERPRESS ARTICLES FOR CURING, AND PULL-OFF AND SHEAR TESTS, ALL OF WHICH ARE BASED ON HERITAGE DESIGNS FROM THE CAI PROGRAM.  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE ON-SITE SUPPORT AT NASA/MSFC DURING THE COUPON COBONDING PROCESS AND GUIDE COUPON FABRICATION. THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE ANALYSIS GUIDANCE FOR RELATING COMPOSITE CREW MODULE TEST DATA TO FLIGHT GEOMETRY BASED ON EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCE WITH PI PREFORM PERFORMANCE.  IN ADDITION, THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE PERFORMANCE SENSITIVITIES TO PARAMETERS SUCH AS OVERWRAP, SUCH THAT THESE CAN BE INCORPORATED INTO THE DESIGN. LUNAR LANDER DEVELOPMENT STUDY  DESCRIPTION STATEMENT:  THIS PUBLICATION IS A BROAD AGENCY ANNOUNCEMENT (BAA) AS CONTEMPLATED BY FEDERAL ACQUISITION REGULATION (FAR) PART 35 AND NASA FEDERAL ACQUISITION REGULATION (NFS) PART 1835.  A FORMAL REQUEST FOR PROPOSAL (RFP), SOLICITATION, AND/OR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION REGARDING THIS ANNOUNCEMENT WILL NOT BE ISSUED.  REQUEST FOR SAME WILL BE DISREGARDED.   NASA WILL NOT ISSUE PAPER COPIES OF THIS ANNOUNCEMENT.  NASA RESERVES THE RIGHT TO SELECT FOR AWARD ALL, SOME, OR NONE OF THE PROPOSALS IN RESPONSE TO THIS ANNOUNCEMENT.  NASA PROVIDES NO FUNDING FOR DIRECT REIMBURSEMENT OF PROPOSAL DEVELOPMENT COSTS.  TECHNICAL AND COST PROPOSALS (OR ANY OTHER MATERIAL) SUBMITTED IN RESPONSE TO THIS BAA WILL NOT BE RETURNED.  IT IS THE POLICY OF NASA TO TREAT ALL PROPOSALS AS SENSITIVE COMPETITIVE INFORMATION AND TO DISCLOSE THEIR CONTENTS ONLY FOR THE PURPOSES OF EVALUATION.    THIS BAA IS SOLICITING PROPOSALS FOR TWO STUDY AREAS.  THE FIRST, CORE STUDY (STUDY AREA 1), IS TITLED DESIGN EVALUATION AND SAFETY IMPROVEMENTS.  STUDY AREA 1 IS BROKEN INTO PARTS 1A AND 1B.  1A SEEKS TO GAIN INDUSTRY INPUT/EVALUATION ON THE TECHNICAL SOLUTION AND VIABILITY OF THE LUNAR DESIGN ANALYSIS CYCLE 1 (LDAC-1) DESIGN AND 1B SEEKS TO DEVELOP AND SUBMIT INNOVATIVE APPROACHES TO IMPROVE THE SAFETY AND RELIABILITY OF THE LDAC-1.  THE SECOND, INCIDENTAL STUDY (STUDY AREA 2), IS TITLED INDUSTRY/GOVERNMENT PARTNERING ARRANGEMENTS AND SEEKS INNOVATIVE APPROACHES TO PROJECT MANAGEMENT AND THE GOVERNMENT - INDUSTRY RELATIONSHIP LEADING UP TO THE PRIME CONTRACTOR EFFORT, WITH THE GOAL OF MINIMIZING DESIGN, DEVELOPMENT, TEST, AND EVALUATION (DDT&E) AND LIFE CYCLE COSTS.  STUDY AREA 2 IS HARDWARE DESIGN RELATED, IN THE SENSE THAT IT SEEKS INDUSTRY INPUT RELATIVE TO THE TEAMING AND IMPLEMENTATION/EXECUTION OF THE TECHNICAL DESIGN REFERENCED IN STUDY AREA 1.  GIVEN THAT STUDY AREA 1 IS THE CORE EMPHASIS OF THE BAA, OFFERORS MAY PROPOSE SOLUTIONS FOR STUDY AREA 1 OR STUDY AREAS 1 AND 2, BUT NOT STUDY AREA 2 EXCLUSIVELY.

THE GOVERNMENT IS PROCURING THE NEXT-GENERATION GEOSTATIONARY OPERATIONAL ENVIRONMENTAL SATELLITES (GOES) SERIES TO CONTINUE ITS MISSION THROUGH NEW REQUIREMENTS SPECIFIED IN THE GOES-R LEVEL I REQUIREMENTS DOCUMENT AND MISSION REQUIREMENTS DOCUMENT (MRD). THE FIRST SATELLITE OF THIS NEW SERIES, DESIGNATED AS GOES-R, WILL PROVIDE THE FIRST MAJOR IMPROVEMENT IN INSTRUMENT TECHNOLOGY SINCE GOES-I LAUNCHED IN 1994. THE GOES-R SERIES WILL INTRODUCE OTHER NEW TECHNOLOGIES IN BOTH THE SPACE AND GROUND SEGMENTS. THESE ADVANCES WILL IMPROVE THE NATION'S ABILITY TO MONITOR AND FORECAST WEATHER AND ENVIRONMENTAL PHENOMENA WITH A SIGNIFICANT INCREASE IN THE NUMBER OF PRODUCTS.  ONE OF NOAA'S PRINCIPAL MISSIONS IS TO PROVIDE FORECASTS AND WARNINGS FOR THE UNITED STATES, ITS TERRITORIES, ADJACENT WATERS AND OCEAN AREA FOR THE PROTECTION OF LIFE AND PROPERTY AND ENHANCEMENT OF THE NATIONAL ECONOMY. THIS MISSION REQUIRES THE CAPABILITY TO ACQUIRE, PROCESS, AND DISSEMINATE ENVIRONMENTAL DATA ON AN EXTENSIVE SPATIAL RANGE (GLOBAL, REGIONAL AND LOCAL) ON A VARIETY OF TIME SCALES. THESE DATA INCLUDE, BUT ARE NOT LIMITED TO: GLOBAL IMAGERY; CLOUD AND PRECIPITATION PARAMETERS; ATMOSPHERIC PROFILES OF TEMPERATURE, MOISTURE, WINDS, AEROSOLS, AND OZONE; SURFACE CONDITIONS CONCERNING ICE, SNOW AND VEGETATION; OCEAN PARAMETERS AND SEA-SURFACE TEMPERATURE; AND SOLAR AND IN-SITU SPACE ENVIRONMENT CONDITIONS.  THE STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW) DEFINES THOSE TASKS TO DESIGN, ANALYZE, VALIDATE, DEVELOP, FABRICATE, ASSEMBLE, INTEGRATE, TEST, VERIFY, EVALUATE, DELIVER GOES-R SERIES SATELLITES AND SUPPORT LAUNCH AND POST LAUNCH, SUPPLY AND MAINTAIN THE GROUND SUPPORT EQUIPMENT (GSE), AND SUPPORT THE NOAA SATELLITE OPERATIONS CONTROL CENTER (SOCC).  THE CONTRACTOR SHALL PROVIDE THE PERSONNEL, MATERIALS, FACILITIES, AND OTHER RESOURCES TO DESIGN, VALIDATE, FABRICATE, ASSEMBLE, INTEGRATE, TEST, VERIFY, AND DELIVER GOES-R SERIES SATELLITES AND PROVIDE PRE-LAUNCH, LAUNCH, AND POST-LAUNCH SUPPORT AND TRAINING UNDER THE BASIC CONTRACT, AND OPTIONS WHEN EXERCISED BY THE GOVERNMENT.

INTERFACE REGION IMAGING SPECTROGRAPH (IRIS) THE IRIS MISSION SHALL PROVIDE THE PERSONNEL, EQUIPMENT AND FACILITIES TO PERFORM THE ANALYSES REQUIRED TO DEFINE THE IRIS SCIENCE INVESTIGATION, SCIENCE PAYLOAD, SPACECRAFT, SCIENCE AND MISSION OPERATIONS CONCEPTS AND THE GROUND DATA SYSTEMS. THE IRIS MISSION SHALL PERFORM THE WORK REQUIRED FOR THE PHASE A STUDY AS DESCRIBED IN THE FOLLOWING SUBSECTIONS AND DOCUMENT IT IN THE FORM OF A CONCEPT STUDY REPORT (CSR).  ALSO, THE IRIS MISSION SHALL PROVIDE A SITE VISIT FOR THE NASA TEAM.  1. THE IRIS TEAM WILL REFINE THE SCIENCE INVESTIGATION AND DESCRIBE IT IN THE CSR.  THIS INCLUDES REFINING THE DE-SCOPE OPTIONS OF THE BASELINE MISSION DEFINED IN THE PROPOSAL. IN ADDITION, THE SCIENCE TEAM SHALL PRODUCE A SCIENCE REQUIREMENTS DOCUMENT.  2. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL DOCUMENT THE EDUCATION, OUTREACH, TECHNOLOGY, AND SMALL DISADVANTAGED BUSINESS PLAN. THIS WILL INCLUDE EDUCATION PROGRAM ACTIVITIES, PUBLIC AWARENESS, AND SMALL DISADVANTAGED BUSINESS PARTICIPATION IN THE MISSION. 3. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL DOCUMENT THE WBS BASELINE, COST BASELINE, AND SCHEDULE BASELINE. THE MANAGEMENT PLAN PROVIDED IN THE PROPOSAL SHALL BE REFINED, COSTS WILL BE ESTIMATED IN GREATER DETAIL, AND DEVELOP AND DOCUMENT RISK DRIVERS AND MITIGATION OPTIONS AND MISSION DE-SCOPE OPTIONS. 4. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL DOCUMENT A SYSTEM ENGINEERING PLAN IN THE CSR. IN ADDITION, THE IRIS TEAM SHALL ALSO REFINE THE MISSION DESIGN OVERVIEW FROM THE PROPOSAL AND DESCRIBE IT IN THE CSR. THIS INCLUDES REQUIREMENTS FLOW DOWN AND TRACEABILITY FROM THE SCIENCE REQUIREMENTS TO THE SPACECRAFT, INSTRUMENT, MISSION OPERATIONS, AND GROUND DATA SYSTEMS REQUIREMENTS, AS WELL AS DESIGN IMPLEMENTATIONS. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL ALSO PROVIDE A PRELIMINARY ORBITAL DEBRIS ANALYSIS ALONG WITH A DRAFT ORBITAL DEBRIS MITIGATION PLAN  5. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL REFINE THE MISSION DESIGN/OPERATIONS CONCEPT AND DESCRIBE IT IN THE CSR. THE DESIGN CONCEPT FULLY DESCRIBES THE OPERATIONAL PHASE OF THE MISSION FROM LAUNCH TO END OF MISSION, INCLUDING DATA DELIVERY. THE MISSION DESIGN WILL INCLUDE THE LAUNCH VEHICLE, MISSION ORBIT, OBSERVATION REQUIREMENTS, DATA VALIDATION REQUIREMENTS, A PRELIMINARY MISSION TIMELINE, AND GROUND STATION SUPPORT REQUIREMENTS. 6. THE IRIS TEAM, SHALL DEVELOP A SPACECRAFT DESIGN SUPPORTING THE PAYLOAD AND MISSION REQUIREMENTS, AND SHALL DESCRIBE THE DESIGN IN THE CSR. THE DESIGN DESCRIPTION WILL FULLY IDENTIFY THE SPACECRAFT SYSTEMS AND DESCRIBE THEIR CHARACTERISTICS AND REQUIREMENTS. THIS WILL INCLUDE A DESCRIPTION OF THE FLIGHT SYSTEM DESIGN, A BLOCK DIAGRAM, A SUMMARY OF THE ESTIMATED PERFORMANCE, AND THE FLIGHT HERITAGE OR RATIONALE USED TO SELECT THE SPACECRAFT SUBSYSTEMS AND COMPONENTS. THE IRIS MISSION WILL PERFORM STUDIES AND ANALYSES TO VALIDATE THE SPACECRAFT DESIGN. THIS INCLUDES, BUT IS NOT LIMITED TO: UPDATED INTEGRATED THERMAL ANALYSIS; POWER SYSTEM ANALYSIS AND SIZING; ATTITUDE CONTROL SYSTEM ANALYSIS; SPACECRAFT STRUCTURAL DESIGN AND ANALYSIS UPDATE; MASS OPTIMIZATION; RADIATION EFFECTS ANALYSIS; AND COMMUNICATIONS ARCHITECTURE AND GROUND SYSTEM OPTIMIZATION. 7. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL REFINE THE INSTRUMENT INTERFACE REQUIREMENTS, AND PROVIDE DOCUMENTATION IN THE CSR THAT INCLUDES POWER, MECHANICAL, THERMAL, COMMAND AND TELEMETRY, ELECTROMAGNETIC COMPATIBILITY AND CONTAMINATION REQUIREMENTS. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL ALSO PROVIDE A PRELIMINARY INSTRUMENT INTEGRATION AND TEST PLAN IN THE CSR THAT WILL DESCRIBE THE TESTING OF SPACECRAFT COMPONENTS PRIOR TO INTEGRATION INTO A SINGLE SYSTEM. 8. THE IRIS TEAM SHALL REFINE AND DOCUMENT THE INVESTIGATION MISSION OPERATIONS AND GROUND OPERATIONS SUPPORT. THIS INCLUDES THE APPROACH FOR MANAGING MISSION OPERATIONS AND FLIGHT OPERATIONS SUPPORT, THE GROUND DATA SYSTEM DEVELOPMENT APPROACH, AND GROUND STATION SUPPORT REQUIREMENTS.

A COMBINATION OF ADVANCED DESIGN AND AN INTEGRATED SYSTEM APPROACH WILL BE TAKEN TO DEFINE A CONCEPTUAL DESIGN THAT MEETS THE ENVIRONMENTAL AND PERFORMANCE GOALS FOR FUTURE SUPERSONIC COMMERCIAL VEHICLES. VIABLE TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT PATHS WILL BE PRODUCED BY THE DESIGN, ENGINEERING AND TEST CAPABILITIES OF OUR TEAM. IN ADDITION, CORE TECHNOLOGY TRADES WILL BE ANALYZED TO PROVIDE QUANTIFIED ESTIMATIONS OF NOISE, EMISSIONS AND PERFORMANCE CHARACTERISTICS OF THE ADVANCED VEHICLE CONCEPT. LOCKHEED MARTIN IS COMMITTED TO HELPING NASA SUCCESSFULLY ACHIEVE THEIR GOALS OF FIRST UNDERSTANDING WHAT IS NECESSARY IN 2030-2035, GENERATING A SUITE OF ENABLING CONCEPTS AND TECHNOLOGIES TO MEET THOSE NEEDS, AND SOCIALIZING THAT VISION WITH THE BROADEST POSSIBLE AUDIENCE. 2.0 OBJECTIVES/GOALS: OBJECTIVE 1: GENERATE PROMISING SUPERSONIC CONCEPTS FOR THE 2030-2035 N+3 TIMEFRAME AND TO DEVELOP PLANS FOR MATURING THE TECHNOLOGIES REQUIRED TO MAKE THOSE CONCEPTS A REALITY. OBJECTIVE 2: FOSTER AN ENVIRONMENT OF INNOVATION TO IDENTIFY CRITICAL ENABLING TECHNOLOGIES FOR PHASE 2 AND BEYOND. OBJECTIVE 3: GENERATE EXCITEMENT BY ESTABLISHING THE RENEWED VIABILITY OF SUPERSONIC TRANSPORT. 3.0 WORK BREAKDOWN STRUCTURE: OVERALL EFFORT IS EIGHTEEN MONTHS, WHICH INCLUDES BY MONTH TWELVE TO DEVELOP THE ADVANCED CONCEPT DESIGN DEFINITION, FIFTEEN MONTHS TO CREATE AND INTEGRATE PARAMETRIC VALUES INTO A RAPID CONCEPTUAL DESIGN (RCD) MODEL WHILE CONDUCTING DESIGN TRADES, AND BY MONTH SIXTEEN TO DEVELOP A TECHNOLOGY ROADMAP, AND BY MONTH EIGHTEEN TO PERFORM RISK ANALYSIS AND GENERATE A FINAL REPORT. THIS WBS ELEMENT ENCOMPASSES ALL WORK NECESSARY TO OVERSEE AND DIRECT THE EXECUTION OF THE N+3 PHASE 1 PROGRAM. LM AERONAUTICS SHALL PLAN, ORGANIZE, CONTROL, DIRECT, STAFF AND SCHEDULE THE N+3 PROGRAM TO ACCOMPLISH PHASE 1 TASKS AND OBJECTIVES.

THE COMET COMA RENDEZVOUS SAMPLE RETURN (CCRSR) MISSION CONCEPT STUDY IS PART OF THE DISCOVERY AND SCOUT MISSION EXPANSION (DSMCE) PROGRAM. THIS CONCEPT STUDY DEVELOP A MISSION (CCRSR) THAT WILL UTILIZE THE ADVANCED STIRLING RADIOISOTOPE GENERATOR (ASRG) ON A SPACECRAFT DESIGNED TO RENDEZVOUS WITH A COMET, MAKE EXTENDED OBSERVATIONS WITHIN THE COMETARY COMA (BUT NOT LAND ON THE COMET), COLLECT COMA SAMPLES, AND RETURN THEM TO EARTH FOR STUDY. THE RETURNED SAMPLES WILL BE STUDIED IN TERRESTRIAL LABORATORIES USING A WIDE VARIETY OF STATE-OF-THE-ART ANALYTICAL TECHNIQUES IN THE SAME MANNER USED TO STUDY SAMPLES RETURNED BY THE STARDUST DISCOVERY MISSION. THE CCRSR MISSION CONCEPT STUDY WAS SELECTED UNDER THE DISCOVERY AND SCOUT MISSION CAPABILITIES EXPANSION CONCEPT STUDIES PROGRAM (DSMCE) (SOLICITATION: NNH07ZDA001N-DSMCE) WITH LOCKHEED MARTIN IDENTIFIED AS A PARTNER. LOCKHEED MARTIN (DENVER) WILL SUPPORT THE WHOLE CCRSR MISSION DESIGN EFFORT WITH AN EMPHASIS ON THE SPACECRAFT BUS, PAYLOAD, AND OPERATIONS. LOCKHEED MARTIN S ANALYSES, TRADES, AND CONCEPTUAL DESIGNS WILL HELP ARC DEVELOP A BRIEFING PACKAGE FOR NASA HEADQUARTERS, AND A FINAL CONCEPT STUDY REPORT (CSR) FOR THE DSMCE PROGRAM.

THE SCOPE OF THIS STATEMENT OF WORK IS TO START THE REDEVELOPMENT/REENGINEERING OF THE ENTIRE EPI INFO SUITE OF PROGRAMS FOLLOWING THE CDC UNIFIED PROCESS FRAMEWORK (CDC UP).  THIS INCLUDES THE PREPARATION AND MAINTENANCE OF PROJECT DOCUMENTATION FOR EACH PHASE OF THE CDC UP: INCEPTION;  ELABORATION;  CREATION;  AND TRANSITION.  IN THE BASE YEAR OF THIS TASK ORDER, IT IS EXPECTED TO COMPLETE ONE FULL ITERATION THROUGH THE CDC UP.  THE INCEPTION PHASE OF THE PROJECT IN THE BASE YEAR WILL BE HEAVILY FOCUSED ON ESTABLISHING THE PROCESSES AND STANDARDS TO BE USED IN THE FOLLOWING PHASES AND IN FUTURE DEVELOPMENT ITERATIONS.  BY THE END OF THE BASE YEAR IT IS EXPECTED TO HAVE DELIVERED THE INTERNATIONAL LOCALIZATION PROCESS COMPLETE, WORKING, AND TESTED; THE PACKAGE AND INSTALLATION PROCESS, COMPLETE, WORKING AND TESTED; AND PROTOTYPES OF EACH OF THE MAJOR AVR (ANALYSIS, VISUALIZATION, AND REPORTING) MODULES OF EPI INFO AS INDICATED IN THE TABLE BELOW.  THE SCOPE OF THIS STATEMENT OF WORK ALSO INCLUDES THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE INTERNATIONAL LOCALIZATION PROCESS FOR THE REDEVELOPED EPI INFO END USER SYSTEM, BUT THE SCOPE DOES NOT INCLUDE ACTUALLY TRANSLATING FROM ENGLISH TO A NON-ENGLISH LANGUAGE.  IN OPTION YEAR 1, IT IS EXPECTED THAT ALL PROGRAMMING AND REENGINEERING OF THE MODULES STARTED IN PROTOTYPE DURING THE BASE YEAR BE COMPLETED BY THE END OF THE FIRST OPTION YEAR.  ALSO IN THE FIRST OPTION YEAR, IT IS EXPECTED THAT THE REMAINING MODULES AND UTILITIES THAT WERE NOT STARTED IN THE BASE YEAR BE PROTOTYPED BY MID YEAR.  ALL PROGRAMMING AND REENGINEERING OF ALL PARTS OF THE EPI INFO SUITE OF TOOLS SHALL BE COMPLETED AND DELIVERED BY THE END OF THE FIRST OPTION YEAR.    IN THE SECOND OPTION YEAR, IT IS EXPECTED TO TRANSITION THE DELIVERED PRODUCT INTO A MAINTENANCE PLAN AND PRIMARILY ENGAGE HELPDESK SUPPORT FOR THE NEW EPI INFO SUITE OF TOOLS.

THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS STATEMENT OF WORK IS TO OBTAIN INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (IT) SUPPORT SERVICES TO ASSIST THE ISA-USAAC (IN CONJUNCTION WITH DEPARTMENT OF ARMY (DA) STAFF) TO CONTINUE DEVELOPMENT OF THE PAYS PROGRAM. PAYS CONSIST OF FOUR PHASES. PHASE I WILL PROVIDE CONTINUED DEVELOPMENT OF WEB-BASED MARKETING MATERIALS AND PROTOTYPE INTERFACES FOR USE BY RECRUITERS, CORPORATE PARTNERS AND DA PERSONNEL. PHASE II WILL PROVIDE A BUSINESS PROCESS REVIEW TO DETERMINE SYSTEM AND DATA RELATIONSHIPS, DATA FLOW AND MODELS. PHASE III ENTAILS THE DEVELOPMENT AND TESTING OF PROTOTYPES ACROSS FUNCTIONAL AREAS. PHASE IV WILL IMPLEMENT APPLICATIONS ACROSS THE FUNCTIONAL AREAS TO INCLUDE INTEGRATING PAYS WITHIN THE G-5 DIRECTORATE.
